Context

This data is from a paper by Kevin Hall and colleagues, titled âUltra-Processed Diets Cause Excess Calorie Intake and Weight Gain: An Inpatient Randomized Controlled Trial of Ad Libitum Food Intake.â. (The data collected in the study are shared publicly at https://osf.io/rx6vm/ as a series of SAS files, and this dataset is a version of the data that has been prepared for you to use in R.)

The authors summarize their work this way:

The perpetual diet wars between factions promoting low-carbohydrate, keto, paleo, high-protein, low-fat, plant-based, vegan, and a seemingly endless list of other diets have led to substantial public confusion and mistrust in nutrition science. While debate rages about the relative merits and demerits of various so-called healthy diets, less attention is paid to the fact that otherwise diverse diet recommendations often share a common piece of advice: avoid ultra-processed foods (Katz and Meller, 2014). Ultra-processed foods have been described as âformulations mostly of cheap industrial sources of dietary energy and nutrients plus additives, using a series of processesâ and containing minimal whole foods (Monteiro et al., 2018)â¦Increased availability and consumption of ultra-processed foods have been associated with rising obesity prevalence, but scientists have not yet demonstrated that ultra-processed food causes obesity or adverse health outcomes. Researchers at the NIH investigated whether people ate more calories when exposed to a diet composed of ultra-processed foods compared with a diet composed of unprocessed foodsâ¦ Subjects were admitted to the NIH Clinical Center and randomized to receive either ultra-processed or unprocessed diets for 2 weeks immediately followed by the alternate diet for 2 weeksâ¦ Despite the ultra-processed and unprocessed diets being matched for daily presented calories, sugar, fat, fiber, and macronutrients, people consumed more calories when exposed to the ultra-processed diet as compared to the unprocessed diet. Furthermore, people gained weight on the ultra-processed diet and lost weight on the unprocessed diet. Limiting consumption of ultra-processed food may be an effective strategy for obesity prevention and treatment.

## Data Access

You can find this dataset at: <https://sldr.netlify.app/data/upf_by_diet.csv>.

## Context

This data is from a paper by Kevin Hall and colleagues, titled ["Ultra-Processed Diets Cause Excess Calorie Intake and Weight Gain: An Inpatient Randomized Controlled Trial of Ad Libitum Food Intake."](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cmet.2019.05.008). (The data collected in the study are shared publicly at <https://osf.io/rx6vm/> as a series of SAS files, and this dataset is a version of the data that has been prepared for you to use in R.) 

The authors summarize their work this way:

>> The perpetual diet wars between factions promoting low-carbohydrate, keto, paleo, high-protein, low-fat, plant-based, vegan, and a seemingly endless list of other diets have led to substantial public confusion and mistrust in nutrition science. While debate rages about the relative merits and demerits of various so-called healthy diets, less attention is paid to the fact that otherwise diverse diet recommendations often share a common piece of advice: avoid ultra-processed foods (Katz and Meller, 2014).
Ultra-processed foods have been described as "formulations mostly of cheap industrial sources of dietary energy and nutrients plus additives, using a series of processes" and containing minimal whole foods (Monteiro et al., 2018)...Increased availability and consumption of ultra-processed foods have been associated with rising obesity prevalence, but scientists have not yet demonstrated that ultra-processed food causes obesity or adverse health outcomes. Researchers at the NIH investigated whether people ate more calories when exposed to a diet composed of ultra-processed foods compared with a diet composed of unprocessed foods... Subjects were admitted to the NIH Clinical Center and randomized to receive either ultra-processed or unprocessed diets for 2 weeks immediately followed by the alternate diet for 2 weeks... Despite the ultra-processed and unprocessed diets being matched for daily presented calories, sugar, fat, fiber, and macronutrients, people consumed more calories when exposed to the ultra-processed diet as compared to the unprocessed diet. Furthermore, people gained weight on the ultra-processed diet and lost weight on the unprocessed diet. Limiting consumption of ultra-processed food may be an effective strategy for obesity prevention and treatment.

## Metadata

This dataset has one row of data per person, per time-period in the study: 

- Baseline (before the person started eating the experimental diets), 
- "Unprocessed" (when they were eating unprocessed foods in the study), and
- "Ultra-processed" (when they were eating ultra-processed foods as part of the study). 

Variables reported in the dataset include:

- `subject_id`, a unique identifier for each of the 20 study participants
- person's `height` in meters
- person's `sex` (recorded values are "Male" or "Female")
- person's `age` in years
- person's `baseline_fat_content` (as a proportion) at the start of the study
- person's `baseline_body_weight` in kilograms at the start of the study
- person's baseline `BMI` (body mass index) at the start of the study
- `baseline_FM`, person's fat mass in kilograms at the start of the study
- `baseline_FFM`, person's fat-free mass in kilograms at the start of the study
- `baseline_REE`, person's resting energy expenditure in calories per day at the start of the study
- `date` of data collection
- `diet`: whether the person was eating "Unprocessed" or "Ultra-processed" food during this time period. "Baseline" means the measurement was taken before the person entered the study (when they were just free to eat anything at home).
- `first_diet`: Which diet did this person eat for the first two weeks of the study? (Half of the people ate Unprocessed first, and the other half at Ultra-processed first; then they switched for the second half of the study.)
- `weight_change` kilograms gained or lost during this part of the study (relative to baseline pre-study weight)
- `FM_change`, change in kilograms of fat mass relative to baseline, during this part of the study
- `FFM_change`, change in kilograms of fat-free mass relative to baseline, during this part of the study
- The study also measured levels of a number of substances of interest in each person's blood. Descriptive details about each one are not given here, so please see the paper for more info if desired. It might be interesting to see if/how each of these changed depending on the diet eaten.
  - `adiponectin` (mg/L)
  - `total_GIP` (pg/mL)
  - `active_GIP` (pg/mL)
  - `FGF21` (pg/mL)
  - `active_ghrelin` (pg/mL)
  - `leptin` (ng/mL)
  - `PYY` (pg/mL)
  - `resistin` (ng/mL)
  - `PAI1` (pg/mL)
  - `active_GLP1` (pg/mL)
  - `glucagon` (pg/mL)
